<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-02T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-02T11:00:00-05:00" n="196" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">862.00/3285: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Austria</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Messersmith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Vienna</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-02T17:00:00+01:00">July 2, 1934—5
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received July 2—2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>77. While complete information still lacking here regarding events
                                Germany following observations may be made: <list>
                                    <label>1.</label>
                                    <item>Noticeable decrease bombing outrages.</item>
                                    <pb facs="0330" n="230" xml:id="pg_230"/>
                                    <label>2.</label>
                                    <item>Austrian frontier guarded against influx fleeing National
                                        Socialists.</item>
                                    <label>3.</label>
                                    <item>Government feels policies regarding Nazis and Germany
                                        vindicated by events and Chancellor has declared stronger
                                        action will be taken against terrorists.</item>
                                    <label>4.</label>
                                    <item>Developments Germany real blow to Austrian Nazi
                                        movement.</item>
                                    <label>5.</label>
                                    <item>Austrian press generally opinion that National Socialism
                                        and Hitler both have lost tremendously in prestige.</item>
                                    <label>6.</label>
                                    <item>Position Chancellor and Government in my opinion much
                                        strengthened.</item>
                                    <label>7.</label>
                                    <item>Situation here entirely quiet.</item>
                                </list></p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Messersmith</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>